{{Infobox book | name = Beyond Natural Selection | image = File:Beyond Natural Selection.jpg | caption = Cover | author = Robert G. Wesson | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = [[Evolution]] | publisher = MIT Press | pub_date = 1991, 1993 | media_type = Print | pages = 369 | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Beyond Natural Selection''''' is a 1991 book by Robert G. Wesson, published by [[MIT Press]].<ref>Ranger-Moore, James. (1992). ''Beyond Natural Selection by Robert G. Wesson''. ''[[Contemporary Sociology]]''. Vol. 21, No. 2. pp. 220-221.</ref><ref>[https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/beyond-natural-selection "Beyond Natural Selection"]. [[MIT Press]].</ref>
Wesson argues for the case of pluralism in [[biology]]. He suggests alternative mechanisms of evolution rather than [[natural selection]]. Wesson argues that [[reductionism]] is inadequate and looks for [[chaos theory]] as an example of a different approach that is needed to explain evolution. The book provides unsolved problems that Wesson believed natural selection could not account for.<ref>Wettersten, John. (1994). ''Beyond Natural Selection by Robert Wesson''. [[Review of Metaphysics]]. Vol. 47, No. 3, pp. 645-647.</ref>
==Reception==
The paleontologist Joseph G. Carter in a critical review for the ''[[American Scientist]]'' wrote the book "includes innumerable oversimplifications and misrepresentations of both evolutionary theory and the paleontological record." Carter noted that the book was filled with errors such as Wesson's claim there is a lack of [[transitional fossil]]s. Carter wrote that the "book approaches the scientific illiteracy" of the intelligent design text ''[[Of Pandas and People]]'', and concluded it was an "embarrassment to the editors of the MIT Press".<ref>Carter, Joseph G. (1992). ''Beyond Natural Selection by Robert Wesson''. ''[[American Scientist]]''. Vol. 80, No. 5. p. 493.</ref>
The ecologist [[Arthur Shapiro (ecologist)|Arthur M. Shapiro]] in a review for ''[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]'' negatively reviewed the book for misunderstanding evolutionary biology and poor scholarship. According to Shapiro he "found an average of just over one error... per page by checking pages of this book at random."<ref>Shapiro, Arthur M. (1993). ''Beyond Natural Selection: A Bradford Book by Robert Wesson''. ''[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]''. Vol. 68, No. 2. p. 266.</ref>
The historian [[Peter J. Bowler]] compared the book to anti-Darwinian and [[Creationism|creationist]] works. He criticized the book for utilizing [[straw man]] arguments and presenting no valid scientific alternative to natural selection. Bowler noted that it is "easy to criticize an established theory, much more difficult to come up with a workable alternative... Hand waving about the creative power of the organism makes a nice-sounding philosophical position but a poor scientific theory".<ref>Bowler, Peter J. (1994). ''Beyond Natural Selection (Paperback Edn) by Robert Wesson''. Biology and Environment: Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy. Vol. 94B, No. 1. p. 98.</ref>
