{{Infobox Book |name = The Behavior of Organisms |title_orig = |translator = |image = File:TheBehaviorOfOrganisms.jpg |image_caption = First edition |author = [[B.F. Skinner]] |illustrator = |cover_artist = |country = United States |language = English |series = |subject = [[Behavior analysis]], [[Behaviorology]] |genre = |publisher = [[Appleton-Century]] |pub_date = 1938 |english_pub_date = |media_type = |pages = 457 |isbn = |oclc = |preceded_by = |followed_by = }} '''''The Behavior of Organisms''''' is [[B.F. Skinner]]'s first book and was published in May 1938 as a volume of the Century Psychology Series.<ref>B.F. Skinner (1938). ''The Behavior of Organisms: An Experimental Analysis.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts: B.F. Skinner Foundation. {{ISBN|1-58390-007-1}}, {{ISBN|0-87411-487-X}}</ref> It set out the parameters for the discipline that would come to be called the [[experimental analysis of behavior]] (EAB) and [[Behavior analysis#21st century behavior analysis|Behavior Analysis]]. This book was reviewed in 1939 by [[Ernest R. Hilgard]].<ref>Ernest R. Hilgard (1939). [http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/pagerender.fcgi?artid=1338876&pageindex=1 "Review of B.F. Skinner's ''The Behavior of Organisms''".] ''Journal of the Experimental Analysis of Behavior'' (1988), 50(2), pp. 283–286.</ref> Skinner looks at science behavior and how the analysis of behavior produces data which can be studied, rather than acquiring data through a conceptual or neural process. In the book, behavior is classified either as respondent or operant behavior, where respondent behavior is caused by an observable stimulus and operant behavior is where there is no observable stimulus for a behavior. The behavior is studied in depth with rats and the feeding responses they exhibit.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skinner|first=B.F.|title=The behavior of organisms: an experimental analysis|year=1938|publisher=Appleton-Century|location=Oxford, England|pages=457}}</ref>
